I just had a couple questions about the origin of the beak. I know
that archaeopteryx is commonly cited as a dinosaur/bird transitional
because it has traits that are otherwise unique to birds and theropod
dinosaurs. Is archaeopteryx a theropod? The main reason I ask is that
I just learned about therizinosaurus and beipiaosaurus, two theropod
dinosaurs that had beaks and feathers. How closely do the beaks
resemble bird beaks? Is it close enough to rule out convergent
evolution? If so, does that rule archaeopteryx out as a direct
ancestor to modern birds? The reason I ask the latter question is
that, as far as I can tell, archaeopteryx was not a theropod. So, it
can't be ancestral to the aforementioned beaked theropods because it
doesn't make sense for theropods (like oh, say, velociraptors) to
evolve into something other than theropods (archaeopteryx), and then
back into theropods (therizinosaurus), so archaeopteryx would have to
be a side branch.

For my second question, I was wondering if anyone could shed some
light on the anatomy of a beak, and how it might evolve from a normal
snout. I'm not asking for individual mutations, of course. It's just
that, when I look at the evolution of forelimbs, it seems pretty
straightforward. Bones changed in shape, duplicated perhaps, and
joints got more flexible and dexterous. Just duplications and
modifications of things that are already there. I always picture beaks
as being these hallow bone-like structures with nasal passages, and
all I can really say about it is &quot;Look, there, that snout got hard and
boney.&quot;
</POST>
