<POSTER> John Harshman &lt;jharshman.diespam...@pacbell.net&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-11-12T10:18:00 </POSTDATE>
<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
The CDesign Proponentist wrote:
&gt; I just had a couple questions about the origin of the beak. I know
&gt; that archaeopteryx is commonly cited as a dinosaur/bird transitional
&gt; because it has traits that are otherwise unique to birds and theropod
&gt; dinosaurs. Is archaeopteryx a theropod?
">

Yes, but so are all birds. That may not be the question you really
wanted to ask.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; The main reason I ask is that
&gt; I just learned about therizinosaurus and beipiaosaurus, two theropod
&gt; dinosaurs that had beaks and feathers. How closely do the beaks
&gt; resemble bird beaks?
">

We can't tell. The beaks themselves are not preserved, only the bones
underneath.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Is it close enough to rule out convergent
&gt; evolution?
">

We can fairly well tell that they are convergent, actually, based on the
distribution of other characters.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; If so, does that rule archaeopteryx out as a direct
&gt; ancestor to modern birds?
">

No. Archaeopteryx probably had a beak too, for one thing. An animal can
have teeth and a beak at the same time, expecially if it's just the
front teeth that are missing. But Archaeopteryx is probably not a direct
ancestor of modern birds.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; The reason I ask the latter question is
&gt; that, as far as I can tell, archaeopteryx was not a theropod. So, it
&gt; can't be ancestral to the aforementioned beaked theropods because it
&gt; doesn't make sense for theropods (like oh, say, velociraptors) to
&gt; evolve into something other than theropods (archaeopteryx), and then
&gt; back into theropods (therizinosaurus), so archaeopteryx would have to
&gt; be a side branch.
">

Again, all the animals you mention here, including living birds, are
theropods. Nothing with a theropod ancestor can ever be a non-theropod.
That's the way cladistic classification works: once a fish, always a fish.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; For my second question, I was wondering if anyone could shed some
&gt; light on the anatomy of a beak, and how it might evolve from a normal
&gt; snout. I'm not asking for individual mutations, of course. It's just
&gt; that, when I look at the evolution of forelimbs, it seems pretty
&gt; straightforward. Bones changed in shape, duplicated perhaps, and
&gt; joints got more flexible and dexterous. Just duplications and
&gt; modifications of things that are already there. I always picture beaks
&gt; as being these hallow bone-like structures with nasal passages, and
&gt; all I can really say about it is &quot;Look, there, that snout got hard and
&gt; boney.&quot;
">

Not bony -- keratinous. The stuff that beaks are made of is the same
stuff that fingernails are made of. Or scales. Or the top layer of your
skin. All that's required is that the skin around the mouth become more
heavilly keratinized, i.e. have more keratin deposited in its upper layers.
</POST>
