Apparently Jixiangornis, Shenzhouraptor, and Hongshanornis have all
been found with beaks, and while scanning through my notes I also see
that an example of Ichthyornis *might* have been found with one. In
addition, I came across this:

The side of the rostrum [of _Changchengornis_], at least on its
rostralmost portion (the only one preserving the lateral
surface), is intensely perforated by longitudinal to suboval
nutrient foramina. As in _Confuciusornis sanctus_, the presence
of a rhamphotheca is suggested by such an intense perforation.
- Chiappe, L. M., Ji S.-A., Ji Q., &amp; M. A. Norell. 1999. Anatomy
and Systematics of the Confuciusornithidae (Theropoda: Aves) from
the Late Mesozoic of Northeastern China. Bulletin of the American
Museum of Natural History 242:50.

I don't know if the absence of such foramina would indicate the
absence of a beak or not.

